<section xml:id="sec-integral-net" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Net Change Theorem and Indefinite Integrals</title>


  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>Interpret a definite integral as net change of a quantity whose rate of change is known.</li>
      <li>Use indefinite integral notation to represent the family of all antiderivatives.</li>
      <li>Compute net change from a velocity (or rate) function using <m>F(b)-F(a)</m>.</li>
      <li>Compute the average value of a function on an interval.</li>
      <li>State and use the Mean Value Theorem for Integrals.</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="ssec-net-change-review">
    <title>Review: Four Meanings of the Definite Integral</title>

    <p>
      The definite integral <m>\displaystyle \int_a^b f(x)\,dx</m> has several complementary interpretations.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <em>Physical:</em> Suppose <m>y</m> and <m>z</m> are physical quantities that depend continuously on an independent variable <m>x</m>,
          with <m>y=f(x)</m> and <m>z=F(x)</m>. If <m>y</m> is the rate of change of <m>z</m>, meaning <m>y=\dfrac{dz}{dx}</m>,
          then the integral of <m>y</m> over <m>[a,b]</m> is the total change in <m>z</m> from <m>x=a</m> to <m>x=b</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          In Leibniz notation, this is written
        </p>

        <me>
          \int_a^b y\,dx \ =\ \left.z\right|_{x=a}^{x=b}.
        </me>

        <p>
          In Newton notation, if <m>f(x)=F'(x)</m>, then
        </p>

        <me>
          \int_a^b f(x)\,dx \ =\ F(b)-F(a),
        </me>

        <p>
          which is the Second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus.
          If an initial value <m>F(a)</m> is known, then
        </p>

        <me>
          F(x)\ =\ F(a) + \int_a^x f(t)\,dt
          \qquad\text{and}\qquad
          F'(x)\ =\ \frac{d}{dx}\left(\int_a^x f(t)\,dt\right)\ =\ f(x),
        </me>

        <p>
          which is the First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <em>Geometric:</em> The integral is the signed area between the graph <m>y=f(x)</m> and the <m>x</m>-axis on <m>[a,b]</m>,
          counting regions above the axis as positive and regions below as negative.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <em>Numerical:</em> Divide <m>[a,b]</m> into <m>n</m> increments of width <m>\Delta x=\dfrac{b-a}{n}</m>.
          Choose sample points <m>x_1,\ldots,x_n</m> (one in each increment).
          Then the integral is approximated by a Riemann sum:
        </p>

        <me>
          \int_a^b f(x)\,dx \ \approx\ \sum_{i=1}^n f(x_i)\,\Delta x
          \ =\ f(x_1)\Delta x + \cdots + f(x_n)\Delta x,
        </me>

        <p>
          and the exact integral is the limit as <m>n\to\infty</m> (so <m>\Delta x\to 0</m>).
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <em>Algebraic:</em> If we can find an antiderivative <m>F</m> with <m>F'(x)=f(x)</m>, then
          <m>\displaystyle \int_a^b f(x)\,dx = F(b)-F(a)</m>.
          Later we will develop systematic methods for finding antiderivatives (for example, substitution, which reverses the Chain Rule).
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="ssec-net-change">
    <title>The Net Change Theorem</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-net-change">
      <title>Net Change Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If a quantity <m>z</m> changes with respect to <m>x</m> at a rate <m>\dfrac{dz}{dx}=f(x)</m>,
          then the net change in <m>z</m> on <m>[a,b]</m> is
        </p>

        <me>
          z(b)-z(a)\ =\ \int_a^b f(x)\,dx.
        </me>

        <p>
          Equivalently, if <m>F'(x)=f(x)</m>, then <m>z(b)-z(a)=F(b)-F(a)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      The phrase <em>net change</em> emphasizes that increases and decreases both count:
      if the rate <m>f(x)</m> is sometimes positive and sometimes negative, the integral records the overall effect.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="ssec-indefinite-integrals">
    <title>Indefinite Integral Notation</title>

    <p>
      Because antiderivatives and integrals are linked by the Fundamental Theorems, we use the integral sign as notation for the most general antiderivative:
    </p>

    <me>
      \int f(x)\,dx \ =\ F(x)+C,
      \qquad\text{where }F'(x)=f(x)\text{ and }C\text{ is any constant}.
    </me>

    <p>
      The expression <m>\displaystyle \int f(x)\,dx</m> is called an <em>indefinite integral</em>.
      It represents a family of functions (all antiderivatives), not a single number.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-indef-int-power">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute <m>\displaystyle \int x^2\,dx</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Since <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}\left(\tfrac13 x^3\right)=x^2</m>, we have
        </p>
        <me>
          \int x^2\,dx \ =\ \tfrac13 x^3 + C.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-net-change-velocity">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A car has velocity <m>v(t)=10t+10\sin(\pi t)</m> (meters per second).
          How far does it travel from <m>t=0</m> to <m>t=3</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Distance traveled is net change in position:
          <m>\displaystyle s(3)-s(0)=\int_0^3 v(t)\,dt</m>.
          First find an antiderivative:
        </p>

        <me>
          \int \left(10t+10\sin(\pi t)\right)\,dt
          \ =\ 5t^2 - \frac{10}{\pi}\cos(\pi t) + C.
        </me>

        <p>
          Now evaluate as a definite integral:
        </p>

        <me>
          \begin{array}{rcl}
          \displaystyle \int_0^3 \left(10t+10\sin(\pi t)\right)\,dt
          &amp;=&amp;
          \left. \left(5t^2 - \frac{10}{\pi}\cos(\pi t)\right)\right|_{t=0}^{t=3}
          \\[0.9em]
          &amp;=&amp;
          \left(5(3^2) - \frac{10}{\pi}\cos(3\pi)\right)
          - \left(5(0^2) - \frac{10}{\pi}\cos(0)\right)
          \\[0.9em]
          &amp;=&amp;
          \left(45 - \frac{10}{\pi}(-1)\right) - \left(0 - \frac{10}{\pi}(1)\right)
          \\[0.9em]
          &amp;=&amp;
          45 + \frac{20}{\pi}
          \ \approx\ 51.4\ \text{meters.}
          \end{array}
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="ssec-average-value">
    <title>Average Value of a Function</title>

    <p>
      In a Riemann sum approximation,
      <m>\sum_{i=1}^n f(x_i)\Delta x</m> can be rewritten to highlight an average of the sample values:
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      \displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^n f(x_i)\Delta x
      &amp;=&amp;
      \displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^n f(x_i)\,\frac{b-a}{n}
      \\[0.9em]
      &amp;=&amp;
      \displaystyle (b-a)\,\frac{f(x_1)+\cdots+f(x_n)}{n}.
      \end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      Taking the limit as <m>n\to\infty</m> motivates the definition of the average value of <m>f</m> on <m>[a,b]</m>:
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-average-value">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <em>average value</em> of <m>f</m> on <m>[a,b]</m> is
        </p>
        <me>
          f_{\text{avg}}
          \ =\
          \frac{1}{b-a}\int_a^b f(x)\,dx.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex-average-sqrt">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the average value of <m>f(x)=\sqrt{x}</m> on <m>[0,4]</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          An antiderivative is <m>\int x^{1/2}\,dx=\frac{2}{3}x^{3/2}+C</m>. Therefore,
        </p>

        <me>
          \begin{array}{rcl}
          \displaystyle f_{\text{avg}}
          &amp;=&amp;
          \displaystyle \frac{1}{4-0}\int_0^4 \sqrt{x}\,dx
          \\[0.9em]
          &amp;=&amp;
          \displaystyle \frac{1}{4}\left.\left(\frac{2}{3}x^{3/2}\right)\right|_{x=0}^{x=4}
          \\[0.9em]
          &amp;=&amp;
          \displaystyle \frac{1}{4}\cdot\frac{2}{3}\cdot 4^{3/2}
          \ =\
          \frac{1}{4}\cdot\frac{2}{3}\cdot 8
          \ =\
          \frac{4}{3}
          \ \approx\ 1.3.
          \end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          Even though <m>\sqrt{x}</m> ranges from 0 to 2 on <m>[0,4]</m>, the average is above 1 because the graph bulges upward.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-average-velocity">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>s(t)</m> be a position function with velocity <m>v(t)=s'(t)</m>.
          Show that the average value of <m>v</m> on <m>[a,b]</m> equals total distance traveled divided by elapsed time.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Using the definition of average value and the Second Fundamental Theorem:
        </p>

        <me>
          \begin{array}{rcl}
          \displaystyle v_{\text{avg}}
          &amp;=&amp;
          \displaystyle \frac{1}{b-a}\int_a^b v(t)\,dt
          \\[0.9em]
          &amp;=&amp;
          \displaystyle \frac{1}{b-a}\int_a^b s'(t)\,dt
          \\[0.9em]
          &amp;=&amp;
          \displaystyle \frac{1}{b-a}\left(s(b)-s(a)\right)
          \ =\
          \frac{s(b)-s(a)}{b-a}.
          \end{array}
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="ssec-mvt-integrals">
    <title>Mean Value Theorem for Integrals</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-mvt-integrals">
      <title>Mean Value Theorem for Integrals</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>, then there exists a point <m>c\in(a,b)</m> such that
        </p>

        <me>
          f(c)\ =\ \frac{1}{b-a}\int_a^b f(x)\,dx.
        </me>

        <p>
          In words: at some point, the function attains its average value.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      <em>Proof idea.</em>
      Let <m>F(x)=\int_a^x f(t)\,dt</m>. By the Mean Value Theorem for derivatives, there is <m>c\in(a,b)</m> such that
      <m>F'(c)=\dfrac{F(b)-F(a)}{b-a}</m>.
      By the First Fundamental Theorem, <m>F'(c)=f(c)</m>.
      Also <m>F(b)-F(a)=\int_a^b f(x)\,dx</m>. Substituting gives the result.
    </p>

    <p>
      In the example <m>f(x)=\sqrt{x}</m> on <m>[0,4]</m>, we found <m>f_{\text{avg}}=\frac{4}{3}</m>.
      So there is <m>c\in(0,4)</m> with <m>\sqrt{c}=\frac{4}{3}</m>, meaning <m>c=\frac{16}{9}</m>.
    </p>
  </subsection>


